name: A Satisfied Mind
author: Glen Campbell
lyrics:
How many times have you heard, someone say.
If I had his money, I would do things my way.
But little do they know, that it's so hard to find.
One rich man in 10, with a satisfied mind.
Well once I was wading in fortune and fame.
Everything I'd ever hoped for, to get a start in life's game.
Then suddenly it happened, well, I lost every dime.
But I'm richer by far, with a satisfied mind.
Money won't buy back your youth when you are old,
or a friend when you are lonely.
Or a love that's grown cold.
The wealthiest person, is a pauper at times.
Compared to the man, with a satisfied mind.

name: The Wall

lyrics:

was a friend of mine, who spent his time, staring at the wall,

you could hear him softly curse,
Nobody at all ever climbed that wall, but I'm gonna be the first,
yeah I'm gonna be the first.
Well the warden walked by and said son don't try,
I'd hate to see you fall,
Cause there aint no doubt they're gonna carry you out, if you ever touch that wall, 
if you ever touch that wall.
Well a years gone by since he made his try, 
but I can still recall, 
how hard he tried and the way he died, but he never made that wall,
no he never made that wall.
There’s never been a man ever shook this can, 
but I know a man who tried,
the newspapers called it a jail break plan, but I know it was suicide,
I know it was suicide.

name: Forty Shades Of Green
author: Johnny Cash
lyrics:
I close my eyes and picture the emerald of the sea, 
      From the fishing boats at Dingle, 
      To the shores of Donagha -dea; 
      I miss the River Shannon, 
      And the folks at Skibbereen, 
      The moorlands and the meadows 
      With their forty shades of green. 
       But most of all I miss a girl in 
       Tipperary town. 
       And most of all I miss her lips, 
       As soft as eider-down; 
       Again I want to see and do 
       The things we've done and seen, 
       With the breeze as sweet as shalamar, 
        And there's forty shades of green. 
      At Dublin's churning surf, 
      I'd love to watch the farmers drain  
     The bogs and spade the turf; 
     To see again the thatches  
     Of the straw the women glean; 
     I'd walk from Cork to Larne to see 
     The forty shades of green.

name: Mama Tried
author: The Everly Brothers
lyrics:
The first thing I remember knowin' was a 
lonesome whistle blowin' and a young'un's 
dream of growing up to ride.
On a freight train leavin' town not knowin' 
where I'm bound and no one could change my 
mind but Mama tried.
One and only rebel child from a family meek 
and mild, my Mama seemed to know what lay 
in store.
In spite of all my Sunday learnin', towards 
the bad I kept a-turnin', til Mama couldn't 
hold me anymore.
And I turned twenty-one in prison doing life 
without parole.
No one could steer me right but Mama tried, 
Mama tried to raise me better but her pleading 
I denied.
That leaves only me to blame, 'cause Mama tried.
Dear old Daddy, rest his soul, left my Mom a 
heavy load.
She tried so very hard to fill his shoes.
Working hours without rest, wanted me to have 
the best.
She tried to raise me right, but I refused.
And I turned twenty-one in prison doing life 
without parole.
No one could steer me right but Mama tried, 
Mama tried to raise me better but her pleading 
I denied.
That leaves only me to blame, 'cause Mama tried.
